    <div class="article-section" id="overview">
      <p>The <strong>Countries of the Realm</strong> are the seven sovereign nations that together constitute <a href="index.html" class="wikilink">Ormandia</a>. Each country retains full internal sovereignty — its own monarch, laws, military, and cultural traditions — while ceding specific powers to the collective governance of the <a href="#" class="wikilink">High Council of Thrones</a> as stipulated in the <a href="#compact" class="wikilink">Compact of Valdenmere</a>.</p>

      <p>The seven nations vary enormously in size, character, and temperament. From the maritime merchant-kingdom of <a href="#craedmoor" class="wikilink">Craedmoor</a> to the austere military republic of <a href="#ironmark" class="wikilink">Ironmark</a>, each country contributes something distinct to the fabric of the Realm — and each carries its own grievances, ambitions, and secrets.</p>

      <div class="compact-note">
        <strong>Note on Sovereignty:</strong> Although all seven nations fall under the Compact's framework, the extent to which each country participates in Realm-wide governance varies. Sylmara, in particular, has historically interpreted its obligations to the High Council in a highly selective manner.
      </div>

      <div class="country-grid">

        <div class="country-card" id="valdenmere">
          <div class="country-card-header">
            <div class="country-emblem">🏰</div>
            <div>
              <div class="country-name">Valdenmere</div>
              <div class="country-tagline">"Where all roads converge"</div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="country-body">
            <p>The seat of the <a href="#" class="wikilink">High Council of Thrones</a> and the cultural capital of all Ormandia, Valdenmere occupies the fertile central plains of the Realm. Its eponymous capital city — a sprawling metropolis of nearly 300,000 souls — is the largest in the Known World. Governed by <a href="royal-houses.html" class="wikilink">House Valdenmyr</a>, the country has held the chairmanship of the High Council for all but forty years of the Compact's existence.</p>
            <p>Valdenmere is known for its universities, its elaborate bureaucracy, and its extraordinary concentration of <a href="#" class="wikilink">Arcane Collegium</a> faculty. It produces little of practical resource but exports law, scholarship, and diplomacy in abundance.</p>
            <div class="country-stats">
              <div class="stat"><div class="stat-value">~3.1M</div><div class="stat-label">Population</div></div>
              <div class="stat"><div class="stat-value">Monarchy</div><div class="stat-label">Government</div></div>
              <div class="stat"><div class="stat-value">Valdenmyr</div><div class="stat-label">Ruling House</div></div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="country-card" id="thorneshire">
          <div class="country-card-header">
            <div class="country-emblem">🌲</div>
            <div>
              <div class="country-name">Thorneshire</div>
              <div class="country-tagline">"The land endures"</div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="country-body">
            <p>The largest of the seven nations by landmass, Thorneshire stretches from the mid-northern highlands to the Heartland Plains. It is predominantly agricultural, with vast wheat and barley farms feeding much of the Realm. The country is governed by <a href="royal-houses.html" class="wikilink">House Thornecroft</a>, a proud and ancient lineage known for its stubbornness and its exceptional cavalry.</p>
            <p>Thorneshire's political culture is conservative and tradition-minded, and its relationship with the more progressive Valdenmere has been a source of friction for generations. The <a href="#" class="wikilink">Thorneshire Dispute</a> of 788 A.C. — over grain taxation — came dangerously close to triggering another Sundering.</p>
            <div class="country-stats">
              <div class="stat"><div class="stat-value">~2.8M</div><div class="stat-label">Population</div></div>
              <div class="stat"><div class="stat-value">Monarchy</div><div class="stat-label">Government</div></div>
              <div class="stat"><div class="stat-value">Thornecroft</div><div class="stat-label">Ruling House</div></div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="country-card" id="ashenvale">
          <div class="country-card-header">
            <div class="country-emblem">🌑</div>
            <div>
              <div class="country-name">Ashenvale</div>
              <div class="country-tagline">"From ash, memory"</div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="country-body">
            <p>The oldest continuously-governed kingdom in Ormandia, Ashenvale's recorded history predates the Compact by nearly four centuries. Its rulers, <a href="royal-houses.html" class="wikilink">House Ashenvale</a> (the country takes its name from the house, a point of considerable national pride), are believed to carry the strongest hereditary arcane sensitivity of any noble bloodline. The country itself is known for its dark, dense forests, its melancholic artistic tradition, and its exceptionally well-preserved libraries.</p>
            <div class="country-stats">
              <div class="stat"><div class="stat-value">~1.6M</div><div class="stat-label">Population</div></div>
              <div class="stat"><div class="stat-value">Monarchy</div><div class="stat-label">Government</div></div>
              <div class="stat"><div class="stat-value">Ashenvale</div><div class="stat-label">Ruling House</div></div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="country-card" id="craedmoor">
          <div class="country-card-header">
            <div class="country-emblem">⚓</div>
            <div>
              <div class="country-name">Craedmoor</div>
              <div class="country-tagline">"The tide favors the bold"</div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="country-body">
            <p>Occupying the entirety of Ormandia's western coast, Craedmoor is the Realm's pre-eminent maritime power. Its merchant fleets operate across three known seas, and its capital, <a href="#" class="wikilink">Port Craeda</a>, is the busiest trading hub in the world. Governed by <a href="royal-houses.html" class="wikilink">House Merwynd</a>, Craedmoor's politics are driven more by commercial interest than dynastic ambition, and its society is notably more open and cosmopolitan than those of its inland neighbors.</p>
            <p>Despite this dominance, large stretches of Craedmoor's nominal western archipelago territory remain effectively governed by the <a href="cultures.html#garroni" class="wikilink">Garroni</a> — a seafaring people who have never been fully integrated into Craedmoor's administration, and whose relationship with the Crown is managed largely through the office of the <a href="royal-houses.html#saltmere" class="wikilink">Margrave of the Saltmere Reaches</a>.</p>
            <div class="country-stats">
              <div class="stat"><div class="stat-value">~2.0M</div><div class="stat-label">Population</div></div>
              <div class="stat"><div class="stat-value">Merchant Crown</div><div class="stat-label">Government</div></div>
              <div class="stat"><div class="stat-value">Merwynd</div><div class="stat-label">Ruling House</div></div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="country-card" id="emberfall">
          <div class="country-card-header">
            <div class="country-emblem">🔥</div>
            <div>
              <div class="country-name">Emberfall</div>
              <div class="country-tagline">"Light born of burning"</div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="country-body">
            <p>The southernmost of the seven nations, Emberfall is a land of dramatic contrasts: scorched red plateaus in the east give way to lush, irrigated valleys in the west, fed by the <a href="#" class="wikilink">River Emara</a>. Its people are known for fierce independence, vivid artisanal crafts, and a passionate devotion to the Flame Aspect of the <a href="#" class="wikilink">Six-Fold Faith</a>. <a href="royal-houses.html" class="wikilink">House Embervane</a> has ruled since the Compact, though succession disputes are a recurring theme.</p>
            <div class="country-stats">
              <div class="stat"><div class="stat-value">~1.2M</div><div class="stat-label">Population</div></div>
              <div class="stat"><div class="stat-value">Monarchy</div><div class="stat-label">Government</div></div>
              <div class="stat"><div class="stat-value">Embervane</div><div class="stat-label">Ruling House</div></div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="country-card" id="sylmara">
          <div class="country-card-header">
            <div class="country-emblem">🌿</div>
            <div>
              <div class="country-name">Sylmara</div>
              <div class="country-tagline">"The forest remembers"</div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="country-body">
            <p>Unlike any other nation in Ormandia, Sylmara operates under a <em>dual governance</em> framework: human nobility led by <a href="royal-houses.html" class="wikilink">House Sylvaran</a> shares political authority with the <a href="#" class="wikilink">Fae Conclave</a>, a council of elder Fae who have inhabited the <a href="#" class="wikilink">Sylmaran Deepwood</a> since before recorded history. This arrangement — enshrined in the <a href="#" class="wikilink">Sylmaran Accord</a> of 178 A.C. — makes Sylmara unique in the Known World and the subject of considerable diplomatic curiosity.</p>
            <div class="country-stats">
              <div class="stat"><div class="stat-value">~0.9M</div><div class="stat-label">Population</div></div>
              <div class="stat"><div class="stat-value">Dual Crown</div><div class="stat-label">Government</div></div>
              <div class="stat"><div class="stat-value">Sylvaran / Fae</div><div class="stat-label">Ruling Body</div></div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="country-card" id="ironmark">
          <div class="country-card-header">
            <div class="country-emblem">⚔</div>
            <div>
              <div class="country-name">Ironmark</div>
              <div class="country-tagline">"Strength is the only truth"</div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="country-body">
            <p>The military heart of Ormandia, Ironmark's culture, economy, and governance are entirely oriented around martial excellence. Situated in the mineral-rich northeastern highlands, it controls the Realm's largest iron and steel production and fields an army widely regarded as the most formidable in the Known World. Technically a monarchy under <a href="royal-houses.html" class="wikilink">House Ironwall</a>, Ironmark is in practice governed by a close partnership between the crown and the <a href="#" class="wikilink">Council of Generals</a>.</p>
            <div class="country-stats">
              <div class="stat"><div class="stat-value">~2.4M</div><div class="stat-label">Population</div></div>
              <div class="stat"><div class="stat-value">Military Crown</div><div class="stat-label">Government</div></div>
              <div class="stat"><div class="stat-value">Ironwall</div><div class="stat-label">Ruling House</div></div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

      </div><!-- end country-grid -->
    </div>

    <div class="article-section" id="compact">
      <h2>The Compact of Valdenmere</h2>
      <p>The <strong>Compact of Valdenmere</strong>, signed in Year 312 A.C. following the conclusion of the <a href="#" class="wikilink">Sundering Wars</a>, is the foundational document of the modern Ormandian political order. It establishes the rights and responsibilities of each member nation, creates the <a href="#" class="wikilink">High Council of Thrones</a>, and sets out the conditions under which military alliance is mandatory.</p>
      <p>The Compact has been amended nine times since its original signing, most significantly in 644 A.C. when Sylmara negotiated the inclusion of Fae representatives in its governance structure, and in 801 A.C. when Ironmark successfully lobbied for a new clause granting military nations double voting weight during declared states of emergency.</p>
      <p>A certified copy of the Compact's original text is held in the <a href="#" class="wikilink">Archive of Valdenmere</a>. Scholars and legal historians consider it one of the most important documents in the history of the Known World.</p>

